oindent \small #2 \medskip\}} % *************************************  egin{document} % ********** USER DEFINED ************* % Enter title here 	itle{From Case Counts to Contact Networks: Inferring Epidemic Coupling in Space and Time} \author{ % Enter author(s) here Adrian Pelcaru,	extsuperscript{1,2} Dirk Brockmann,	extsuperscript{1,2} } { % Enter affiliation(s) here 1. Dresden University of Technology, Dresden, Saxony, Germany\ 2. Center Synergy of Systems, Dresden, Saxony, Germany } % Enter abstract here. Please keep everything within one page. The recent COVID-19 pandemic constituted a worldwide epidemic that unfolded on a heterogeneous mobility network, coupling local transmission to long-range inter-regional connectivity. Beyond spatial coupling, regional seasonality and non-pharmaceutical interventions introduced strong temporal modulation of the effective contact rate, varying in space and time. Previous work has shown that the effective distance between countries realized by the air transportation network predicts the arrival times of a pandemic [1]. Inferring spatio–temporal transmission structure from incidence data alone, however, remains a central problem in epidemiology, with implications for real-time surveillance and for the interpretion of mobility and contact information. We analyse discrete-time renewal SIRS models on a network of metapopulations that incorporate infection-age structure, seasonality and mobility between regions, and time-varying local contact rates (Fig. 1b). In the analysis, these ingredients are combined into an effective spatio–temporal contact kernel that quantifies how cases in region $m$ at a given infection age contribute to new infections in region $n$ one day ahead. Stacking multi-region incidence histories across lags into a delay-embedded state, the renewal dynamics define a map on this reconstructed space whose local Jacobian [2] is the convolution operator determined by the kernel and the susceptible pools. Aggregating the kernel over infection age with suitable weights yields a time-dependent effective contact matrix ($K_{nm}(t)$, Fig. 1a) and associated effective distances that extract the substrate on which infections propagate between regions. This construction provides a transparent link between mechanistic assumptions about mobility and varying infection rates and the resulting effective couplings in space and time, and identifies a natural operator that can, in principle, be compared to reconstructions from incidence data to detect systematic deviations from mobility-based expectations. % igskip {\small 
oindent[1] Dirk Brockmann and Dirk Helbing, Science (2013)\ 
